Hi @svdo,

I guess the error is due to wrong URLs in the projects.json. For instance, taking as a reference the call at: `https://gitlab.my-enterprise.com/api/v4/projects/my-project%2Fmy-repo.git/issues?updated_after=1970-01-01T00%3A00%3A00%2B00%3A00&sort=asc&per_page=100&order_by=updated_at&state=all`, it fails since there is no project `my-project%2Fmy-repo.git` (the one available via the API is my-project%2Fmy-repo).

Please, try to remove the `.git`. from your projects.json
```
{
  "my-project": {
    "meta": {
      "title": "my-project"
    },
    "git": [
      "https://user:token@gitlab.my-enterprise.com/my-project/my-repo"
    ],
    "gitlab:issue": [
      "https://user:token@gitlab.my-enterprise.com/my-project/my-repo"
    ],
    "gitlab:merge": [
      "https://user:token@gitlab.my-enterprise.com/my-project/my-repo"
    ],
    "colic": [
      "https://user:token@gitlab.my-enterprise.com/my-project/my-repo"
    ],
    "cocom": [
      "https://user:token@gitlab.my-enterprise.com/my-project/my-repo"
    ]
  }
}
```

WRT '%2F' there shouldn't be any problem. The URL defined in the projects.json is passed to perceval, which creates the correct endpoint for first-level projects (e.g., https://github.com/chaoss/grimoirelab-perceval/blob/master/perceval/backends/core/gitlab.py#L644). In case of error, the exception is propagated to ELK, which prints the repo URL where the fail occurred (without '%2F').

Note that in case your gitlab project is nested, the URL should be:
`https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/my-project%2my-sub-project`

Let me know if this solves your issue,
Valerio
